<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════
     LESSON 1.1 — Classification of Matter
══════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="lesson-start" id="l1-1">
  <span class="lesson-tag lt-u1">Lesson 1.1</span>
  <h3>Classification of Matter & State Changes</h3>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h4>Pure Substance vs Mixture</h4>
  <div class="kbox kbox-green">
    <span class="kbox-label">Definition</span>
    A <strong>pure substance</strong> has a fixed, uniform chemical composition throughout — one type of particle.<br>
    A <strong>mixture</strong> contains two or more substances mixed together without chemical reaction.
  </div>

  <div class="g2">
    <table class="ctable">
      <tr><th>Pure Substances</th><th>Examples</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Elements</td><td>H₂, O₂, Fe, Cu, Na, C (diamond/graphite)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Compounds</td><td>H₂O, NaCl, CO₂, HCl, CH₃COOH, CuO</td></tr>
    </table>
    <table class="ctable">
      <tr><th>Mixtures</th><th>Examples</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Homogeneous</td><td>Saline solution, air, medical alcohol (75% ethanol), hydrochloric acid (gas dissolved)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Heterogeneous</td><td>Sand + water, concrete, muddy water</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="etip"><p><strong>Ice + water = pure substance</strong> (both are H₂O, just different states). Distilled water = pure substance. Hydrochloric acid = mixture (HCl gas + H₂O). Medical alcohol = mixture (75% C₂H₅OH + 25% H₂O).</p></div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h4>Elements: Isotopes vs Allotropes</h4>
  <div class="g2">
    <div class="kbox kbox-blue">
      <span class="kbox-label">Isotopes</span>
      <strong>Same element, different neutron number.</strong><br>
      Same protons (Z), same chemical behaviour, different mass.<br><br>
      Examples: ¹²C and ¹³C and ¹⁴C (all carbon, Z=6)<br>
      ¹H (protium), ²H (deuterium), ³H (tritium)<br>
      ³⁵Cl and ³⁷Cl
    </div>
    <div class="kbox kbox-amber">
      <span class="kbox-label">Allotropes</span>
      <strong>Same element, different structural arrangement.</strong><br>
      Different physical properties, different forms.<br><br>
      Carbon: diamond, graphite, C₆₀ (buckminsterfullerene)<br>
      Oxygen: O₂ (oxygen) and O₃ (ozone)<br>
      Phosphorus: white P and red P
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="etip"><p>¹²C and ¹⁴C are <strong>isotopes</strong> (different neutrons). Diamond and graphite are <strong>allotropes</strong> (same carbon atoms, different structure). CO and CO₂ are different <strong>compounds</strong> — NOT allotropes.</p></div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h4>Chemical Change vs Physical Change</h4>
  <div class="g2">
    <div class="kbox kbox-red">
      <span class="kbox-label">Chemical Change — New substance formed</span>
      Iron rusting (Fe → Fe₂O₃)<br>
      Combustion (CH₄ + O₂ → CO₂ + H₂O)<br>
      Neutralisation (HCl + NaOH → NaCl + H₂O)<br>
      Electrolysis (2H₂O → 2H₂ + O₂)<br>
      Food spoiling, fermentation
    </div>
    <div class="kbox kbox-blue">
      <span class="kbox-label">Physical Change — No new substance formed</span>
      Ice melting (H₂O solid → liquid)<br>
      Dissolving sugar in water<br>
      <strong>Activated carbon adsorbing pigments</strong> ← adsorption, NOT chemical!<br>
      Volatilisation of HCl from concentrated acid<br>
      Distillation, filtration, crystallisation
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="etip"><p><strong>Activated carbon adsorbing colour</strong> is a PHYSICAL change (adsorption = surface attraction, no bonds broken/formed). This is a very common exam trap!</p></div>
</div>

<!-- ── COMMON MISTAKES 1.1 ── -->
<div class="mistake-section">
  <div class="ms-head">❌ Common Mistakes — Lesson 1.1</div>

  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "Saline solution is a pure substance because it looks uniform."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: Saline = NaCl dissolved in H₂O = homogeneous MIXTURE (two different compounds).</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">Homogeneous means same throughout, but it is still a mixture if it contains two or more substances.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "CO and CO₂ are allotropes of carbon."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: CO and CO₂ are different COMPOUNDS of carbon and oxygen. Allotropes must be the PURE ELEMENT in different forms.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">Allotropes: same element only. Diamond/graphite = carbon allotropes ✓. CO/CO₂ = different compounds ✗.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "¹²C and ¹³C are allotropes because both are carbon."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: They are ISOTOPES — same element (Z=6), different neutron number (6 vs 7).</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">Isotopes differ in neutron count and mass number; allotropes differ in bonding/structure.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "Activated carbon decolourising a solution is a chemical change."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: It is PHYSICAL (adsorption). No new substance is formed; the pigment molecules attach to the carbon surface by physical forces.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">Key test: is a new substance formed? For adsorption = no → physical change.</div>
  </div>
</div>

