<div class="lesson-start" id="l1-2">
  <span class="lesson-tag lt-u1">Lesson 1.2</span>
  <h3>Chemical Notation & Writing Equations</h3>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h4>Reading Chemical Symbols</h4>
  <div class="g3">
    <div class="mini">
      <div class="mh">Atoms & Molecules</div>
      <ul>
        <li>3O = 3 oxygen <strong>atoms</strong></li>
        <li>3O₂ = 3 oxygen <strong>molecules</strong></li>
        <li>2H₂ = 2 hydrogen molecules</li>
        <li>4H₂O = 4 water molecules</li>
        <li>Large coefficient: number of molecules/formula units</li>
        <li>Subscript: atoms per molecule</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="mini">
      <div class="mh">Ions Notation</div>
      <ul>
        <li>5Na⁺ = 5 sodium ions</li>
        <li>3SO₄²⁻ = 3 sulfate ions</li>
        <li>Ca²⁺ = calcium(II) ion</li>
        <li>Fe³⁺ = iron(III) ion</li>
        <li>OH⁻ = hydroxide ion</li>
        <li>NH₄⁺ = ammonium ion</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="mini">
      <div class="mh">Common Naming Traps</div>
      <ul>
        <li>NaNO₂ = sodium <strong>nitrite</strong></li>
        <li>NaNO₃ = sodium nitrate</li>
        <li>Na₃N = sodium nitride</li>
        <li>CH₃CH₂OH = <strong>ethanol</strong> (NOT ethanal)</li>
        <li>CH₃CHO = ethanal (aldehyde)</li>
        <li>CO = carbon <strong>mono</strong>xide</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h4>Six Types of Chemical Reactions</h4>
  <table class="ctable">
    <tr><th>Type</th><th>Pattern</th><th>Example</th><th>Key feature</th></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Combination</strong></td><td>A + B → AB</td><td>2H₂ + O₂ → 2H₂O</td><td>Two reactants → one product</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Decomposition</strong></td><td>AB → A + B</td><td>2NaHCO₃ →(Δ) Na₂CO₃ + CO₂↑ + H₂O</td><td>One reactant → multiple products</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Single Displacement</strong></td><td>A + BC → AC + B</td><td>Fe + CuSO₄ → FeSO₄ + Cu</td><td>Element displaces element from compound</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Double Displacement</strong></td><td>AB + CD → AD + CB</td><td>BaCl₂ + H₂SO₄ → BaSO₄↓ + 2HCl</td><td>Ions swap partners</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Neutralisation</strong></td><td>Acid + Base → Salt + H₂O</td><td>HCl + NaOH → NaCl + H₂O</td><td>Subtype of double displacement</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Redox</strong></td><td>Oxidation states change</td><td>2Fe + 3Cl₂ → 2FeCl₃</td><td>Electron transfer occurs</td></tr>
  </table>
  <div class="etip"><p>HCl + NaOH is classified as <strong>neutralisation</strong> (most specific) AND double displacement. On the CSCA exam, always choose the most specific classification.</p></div>

  <div class="eq" style="margin-top:14px;">
<span class="ec">— Key reactions to memorise —</span>
2NaHCO₃ →(Δ) Na₂CO₃ + CO₂↑ + H₂O  (decomposition; heating baking soda)
CaCO₃ →(Δ, high temp) CaO + CO₂↑     (industrial; limestone → quicklime)
Fe + CuSO₄ → FeSO₄ + Cu              (single displacement; iron displaces copper)
3Fe + 4H₂O →(high T) Fe₃O₄ + 4H₂    (iron + steam at high temperature)
2Na + 2H₂O → 2NaOH + H₂↑            (sodium + cold water; vigorous)
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ── COMMON MISTAKES 1.2 ── -->
<div class="mistake-section">
  <div class="ms-head">❌ Common Mistakes — Lesson 1.2</div>

  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "NaNO₂ is called sodium nitrate."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: NaNO₂ = sodium <em>nitrite</em>. NaNO₃ = sodium nitrate. Na₃N = sodium nitride.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">-ite = one fewer oxygen than -ate. The -ide suffix refers to a completely different anion (the element itself, like N³⁻).</div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "Fe + CuSO₄ → FeSO₄ + Cu is a double displacement reaction."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: It is a SINGLE displacement — iron (an element) displaces copper (another element) from a compound.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">Double displacement: two COMPOUNDS swap ions. Single displacement: one FREE element displaces another element from a compound.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "HCl + NaOH → NaCl + H₂O is a decomposition reaction."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: HCl + NaOH is a NEUTRALISATION reaction (acid + base → salt + water). It is also a double displacement, but NOT decomposition.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">Decomposition = one reactant breaks down. Here we have TWO reactants, so it cannot be decomposition.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "CH₃CH₂OH is named ethanal."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: CH₃CH₂OH = <em>ethanol</em> (an alcohol, –OH group). Ethanal = CH₃CHO (an aldehyde, –CHO group). These are completely different compounds.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">Ethanol ends in –ol (alcohol). Ethanal ends in –al (aldehyde). Check the functional group!</div>
  </div>
</div>

