     LESSON 1.3 — Solution Concentration & pH
══════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="lesson-start" id="l1-3">
  <span class="lesson-tag lt-u1">Lesson 1.3</span>
  <h3>Solution Concentration & pH Calculations</h3>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h4>Molar Concentration</h4>
  <div class="g2">
    <div>
      <div class="kbox kbox-green">
        <span class="kbox-label">Formula</span>
        <strong>c = n / V</strong><br>
        c = molar concentration (mol·L⁻¹)<br>
        n = amount of solute (mol) = m/M<br>
        V = volume of <em>solution</em> (not solvent!) in litres
      </div>
      <div class="kbox kbox-amber">
        <span class="kbox-label">CRITICAL Rule</span>
        Molar concentration is an <strong>intensive property</strong>.<br>
        Taking any volume from a uniform solution → same concentration.<br><br>
        ✓ 50 mL taken from 1 L of 1 mol·L⁻¹ NaOH → still <strong>1 mol·L⁻¹</strong><br>
        ✗ NOT 0.05 mol·L⁻¹ (that confuses moles with concentration)
      </div>
    </div>
    <div>
      <div class="kbox kbox-blue">
        <span class="kbox-label">Concentration vs Mass Fraction</span>
        <strong>Mass fraction (ω):</strong><br>
        ω = m(solute) / m(solution) × 100%<br><br>
        <strong>Conversion formula:</strong><br>
        c = 1000ρω / M<br>
        ρ = density (g·mL⁻¹), M = molar mass
      </div>
      <div class="kbox kbox-red">
        <span class="kbox-label">Saturated Solution Trap</span>
        Saturated at constant T:<br>
        • Evaporate solvent → salt crystallises out → concentration stays SATURATED (same ω for KNO₃)<br>
        • But: adding more solvent to saturated → less concentrated (diluted)<br>
        • Adding more solute to saturated → stays saturated (excess remains solid)
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h4>pH Calculations</h4>
  <div class="g2">
    <div>
      <div class="kbox kbox-red">
        <span class="kbox-label">Formula</span>
        <strong>pH = −log[H⁺]</strong><br>
        At 25°C: pH + pOH = 14<br><br>
        pH &lt; 7: acidic solution<br>
        pH = 7: neutral solution<br>
        pH &gt; 7: basic/alkaline solution
      </div>
      <table class="ctable" style="margin-top:10px;">
        <tr><th>Solution</th><th>[H⁺] mol/L</th><th>pH</th></tr>
        <tr><td>0.001 mol/L HCl</td><td>10⁻³</td><td><strong>3</strong></td></tr>
        <tr><td>0.1 mol/L HCl</td><td>10⁻¹ = 0.1</td><td><strong>1</strong></td></tr>
        <tr><td>0.1 mol/L H₂SO₄</td><td>0.2 (diprotic!)</td><td><strong>≈0.7</strong></td></tr>
        <tr><td>0.1 mol/L NaOH</td><td>10⁻¹³</td><td><strong>13</strong></td></tr>
        <tr><td>0.1 mol/L CH₃COOH</td><td>~10⁻³ (partial)</td><td><strong>~2.9</strong></td></tr>
      </table>
    </div>
    <div>
      <div class="kbox kbox-amber">
        <span class="kbox-label">H₂SO₄ — DIPROTIC ACID TRAP!</span>
        H₂SO₄ is a diprotic (2 protons) strong acid:<br>
        H₂SO₄ → 2H⁺ + SO₄²⁻<br><br>
        <strong>0.1 mol/L H₂SO₄:</strong><br>
        [H⁺] = 2 × 0.1 = 0.2 mol/L<br>
        pH = −log(0.2) ≈ 0.70<br>
        <strong>NOT pH = 1!</strong> (pH=1 would be HCl)<br><br>
        This is why 0.1 mol/L H₂SO₄ does NOT have pH=1.
      </div>
      <div class="kbox kbox-blue" style="margin-top:10px;">
        <span class="kbox-label">Common Indicators</span>
        <strong>Litmus:</strong> red in acid, blue in base<br>
        <strong>Phenolphthalein:</strong> colourless in acid/neutral → pink in base<br>
        <strong>NH₄Cl</strong> solution: acidic (hydrolysis)<br>
        <strong>Na₂CO₃</strong> solution: basic (hydrolysis)<br>
        <strong>NaCl</strong> solution: neutral (no hydrolysis)
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ── COMMON MISTAKES 1.3 ── -->
<div class="mistake-section">
  <div class="ms-head">❌ Common Mistakes — Lesson 1.3</div>

  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "0.1 mol/L H₂SO₄ has pH = 1."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: 0.1 mol/L H₂SO₄ → [H⁺] = 2 × 0.1 = 0.2 mol/L → pH = −log(0.2) ≈ 0.70.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">H₂SO₄ is diprotic — it releases 2 H⁺ ions per molecule. So the H⁺ concentration is TWICE the acid concentration.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "Taking 50 mL from 1 L of 1 mol·L⁻¹ NaOH gives a 0.05 mol·L⁻¹ solution."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: The 50 mL sample still has concentration 1 mol·L⁻¹. (You have 0.05 mol of NaOH, but in 0.05 L → c = 0.05/0.05 = 1 mol·L⁻¹.)</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">Concentration does NOT change when you take a portion of a uniform solution. Only the AMOUNT (moles) changes, not the concentration.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "0.1 mol/L CH₃COOH has pH = 1 like HCl."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: CH₃COOH is a WEAK acid — only partially ionises. 0.1 mol/L gives pH ≈ 2.9 (much less acidic than 0.1 mol/L HCl at pH=1).</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">Strong acids fully ionise (HCl→H⁺+Cl⁻, 100%). Weak acids partially ionise (CH₃COOH⇌H⁺+CH₃COO⁻, ~1.3%). Much lower [H⁺] → higher pH.</div>
  </div>
</div>

