<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════
     LESSON 1.4 — Amount of Substance
══════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="lesson-start" id="l1-4">
  <span class="lesson-tag lt-u1">Lesson 1.4</span>
  <h3>Amount of Substance — The Mole</h3>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h4>Core Mole Formulae</h4>
  <div class="g3">
    <div class="kbox kbox-green">
      <span class="kbox-label">Amount from Mass</span>
      <strong>n = m / M</strong><br>
      n = moles (mol)<br>
      m = mass (g)<br>
      M = molar mass (g/mol)
    </div>
    <div class="kbox kbox-blue">
      <span class="kbox-label">Amount from Particles</span>
      <strong>n = N / Nₐ</strong><br>
      N = number of particles<br>
      Nₐ = 6.02 × 10²³ mol⁻¹<br>
      (Avogadro's number)
    </div>
    <div class="kbox kbox-amber">
      <span class="kbox-label">Amount from Gas Volume (STP)</span>
      <strong>n = V / 22.4</strong><br>
      V = volume in litres at STP<br>
      STP = 0°C, 1 atm<br>
      Molar volume = 22.4 L/mol
    </div>
  </div>

  <table class="ctable" style="margin-top:14px;">
    <tr><th>Substance</th><th>Molar Mass (g/mol)</th><th>Key to remember</th></tr>
    <tr><td>H₂O</td><td>18</td><td>2(1)+16</td></tr>
    <tr><td>NaOH</td><td>40</td><td>23+16+1</td></tr>
    <tr><td>HCl</td><td>36.5</td><td>1+35.5</td></tr>
    <tr><td>CO₂</td><td>44</td><td>12+2(16)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>CuO</td><td>79.5≈80</td><td>64+16 (Cu=63.5 or 64)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Na₂CO₃</td><td>106</td><td>2(23)+12+3(16)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>H₂SO₄</td><td>98</td><td>2(1)+32+4(16)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>NaHCO₃</td><td>84</td><td>23+1+12+3(16)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>I₂</td><td>254</td><td>2(127)</td></tr>
  </table>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h4>Counting Atoms — Strategy</h4>
  <div class="kbox kbox-purple">
    <span class="kbox-label">Method</span>
    Total atoms = moles of compound × atoms per molecule × Nₐ<br>
    Or in mol-atom terms: mol-atoms = mol × atoms per formula unit
  </div>

  <table class="ctable" style="margin-top:10px;">
    <tr><th>Substance & Amount</th><th>Formula atoms</th><th>Total mol-atoms</th><th>Rank</th></tr>
    <tr><td>1 mol CH₄</td><td>1C + 4H = 5</td><td>5 mol atoms</td><td>2nd</td></tr>
    <tr><td>1.5 mol CO₂</td><td>1C + 2O = 3</td><td>4.5 mol atoms</td><td>3rd</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>2 mol H₂S</strong></td><td>2H + 1S = 3</td><td><strong>6 mol atoms ✓ MOST</strong></td><td>1st</td></tr>
    <tr><td>1.5 mol H₂O</td><td>2H + 1O = 3</td><td>4.5 mol atoms</td><td>3rd</td></tr>
    <tr><td>11.2 L CH₄ at STP</td><td>= 0.5 mol × 5 atoms</td><td>2.5 mol atoms</td><td>4th</td></tr>
    <tr><td>2 g He</td><td>= 1 mol × 1 atom</td><td>1 mol atom (Nₐ particles)</td><td>5th</td></tr>
    <tr><td>1 mol HF</td><td>1H + 1F = 2</td><td>2 mol atoms</td><td>5th</td></tr>
  </table>
  <div class="etip"><p>Always convert to moles FIRST, then multiply by atoms per formula unit. Don't forget: 11.2 L at STP = 0.5 mol (not 1 mol)!</p></div>
</div>

<!-- ── COMMON MISTAKES 1.4 ── -->
<div class="mistake-section">
  <div class="ms-head">❌ Common Mistakes — Lesson 1.4</div>

  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "11.2 L of any gas at STP = 1 mol."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: 11.2 L at STP = 0.5 mol. Only 22.4 L = 1 mol at STP.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">n = V/22.4. So 11.2/22.4 = 0.5 mol. Don't assume 11.2 L = 1 mol — a very common error!</div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "M(CuO) = 64 g/mol because Cu=64 and O=16 gives 80, but the question says 64."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: M(CuO) = 63.5 + 16 = 79.5 ≈ 79.6 g/mol (using Cu=63.5). The CSCA exam uses Cu=64, giving M(CuO)=80 g/mol.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">Always check atomic weights given at the start of the CSCA paper: O:16, Na:23, Cu:64, H:1, C:12. Using these: M(CuO) = 64+16 = 80 g/mol.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "1 mol H₂ has 2 mol atoms, and 1 mol CH₄ has 4 mol atoms."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: 1 mol CH₄ has 5 mol atoms (1C + 4H). H₂ has 2 mol atoms (both H). Count ALL atoms in the formula!</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">CH₄ has FIVE atoms: one carbon and four hydrogens = 5 atoms per molecule.</div>
  </div>
</div>

