     LESSON 1.5 — Ideal Gas Law
══════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="lesson-start" id="l1-5">
  <span class="lesson-tag lt-u1">Lesson 1.5</span>
  <h3>Ideal Gas Law & Applications</h3>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h4>The Ideal Gas Law</h4>
  <div class="g2">
    <div>
      <div class="kbox kbox-green">
        <span class="kbox-label">Main Formula</span>
        <strong>PV = nRT</strong><br>
        P = pressure (Pa or atm)<br>
        V = volume (m³ or L)<br>
        n = amount (mol)<br>
        R = 8.314 J·mol⁻¹·K⁻¹<br>
        T = temperature (K = °C + 273)
      </div>
      <div class="kbox kbox-amber">
        <span class="kbox-label">At STP (Standard Conditions)</span>
        T = 0°C = 273 K, P = 1 atm = 101.3 kPa<br>
        <strong>Molar volume = 22.4 L/mol</strong><br>
        n = V / 22.4 (V in litres)
      </div>
    </div>
    <div>
      <table class="ctable">
        <tr><th>Gas Law</th><th>Condition</th><th>Formula</th></tr>
        <tr><td>Boyle's Law</td><td>T constant</td><td>P₁V₁ = P₂V₂</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Charles's Law</td><td>P constant</td><td>V₁/T₁ = V₂/T₂</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Gay-Lussac's</td><td>V constant</td><td>P₁/T₁ = P₂/T₂</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Combined</td><td>—</td><td>P₁V₁/T₁ = P₂V₂/T₂</td></tr>
      </table>
      <div class="kbox kbox-red" style="margin-top:10px;">
        <span class="kbox-label">CRITICAL: STP vs Room Temperature</span>
        22.4 L/mol is ONLY at STP (0°C, 1 atm).<br>
        At room temperature (25°C), molar volume ≈ 24.5 L/mol.<br>
        Always check the conditions stated in the question!
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ── COMMON MISTAKES 1.5 ── -->
<div class="mistake-section">
  <div class="ms-head">❌ Common Mistakes — Lesson 1.5</div>

  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "22.4 L/mol applies at room temperature (25°C)."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: 22.4 L/mol applies ONLY at STP (0°C, 1 atm). At 25°C, molar volume ≈ 24.5 L/mol.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">Always check: the question says "standard conditions" → use 22.4 L/mol. If not specified, be careful.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "Temperature in the gas law can be in °C."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: ALWAYS convert to Kelvin: T(K) = T(°C) + 273. Charles's Law fails if you use °C.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">0°C = 273 K. 25°C = 298 K. 100°C = 373 K. The gas laws only work with absolute temperature.</div>
  </div>
</div>

