<!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════
     CHAPTER 1 SUMMARY — WHAT YOU MUST OWN
════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="summary-section" id="ch1-summary">
  <div class="sum-head">📌 Chapter 1 Summary — What You MUST Own</div>
  <div class="must-own-grid">
    <div class="must-item">
      <div class="mi-title">1. Matter Classification</div>
      <div class="mi-body">Pure substance = one type of particle. Mixture = two or more substances. Ice+water = pure (all H₂O). Medical alcohol = mixture. Isotopes = same Z, different neutrons. Allotropes = same element, different structure.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="must-item">
      <div class="mi-title">2. Chemical Change</div>
      <div class="mi-body">New substance formed = chemical change. Adsorption, dissolving, state changes = physical. Activated carbon adsorbing pigments = PHYSICAL (most common trap on exam).</div>
    </div>
    <div class="must-item">
      <div class="mi-title">3. Naming Compounds</div>
      <div class="mi-body">NaNO₂ = nitrite (not nitrate). CH₃CH₂OH = ethanol (not ethanal). CH₃CHO = ethanal. CO = carbon monoxide. Study the naming rules — naming errors cost easy marks.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="must-item">
      <div class="mi-title">4. Reaction Types</div>
      <div class="mi-body">6 types: combination, decomposition, single displacement, double displacement, neutralisation, redox. HCl + NaOH = neutralisation (most specific). Fe + CuSO₄ = single displacement (not double).</div>
    </div>
    <div class="must-item">
      <div class="mi-title">5. pH Calculations</div>
      <div class="mi-body">pH = −log[H⁺]. H₂SO₄ is diprotic: 0.1 mol/L → [H⁺]=0.2 → pH≈0.7 (NOT 1). Weak acids (CH₃COOH) partially ionise → higher pH than same concentration of strong acid. 0.001 mol/L HCl = pH 3.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="must-item">
      <div class="mi-title">6. Molar Concentration</div>
      <div class="mi-body">c = n/V. Taking a sample from a uniform solution does NOT change concentration. 50 mL of 1 mol/L NaOH taken from 1 L → still 1 mol/L. Only the moles (n) change, not c.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="must-item">
      <div class="mi-title">7. Mole Calculations</div>
      <div class="mi-body">n=m/M=N/Nₐ=V/22.4 (at STP). 11.2 L at STP = 0.5 mol (NOT 1 mol). Count atoms = mol × atoms per formula unit. CSCA atomic weights: O=16, Na=23, Cu=64, H=1, C=12.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="must-item">
      <div class="mi-title">8. Ideal Gas Law</div>
      <div class="mi-body">PV=nRT. Always use Kelvin (T=°C+273). 22.4 L/mol at STP ONLY (0°C, 1 atm). At 25°C molar volume ≈ 24.5 L/mol. Boyle's: P₁V₁=P₂V₂. Charles's: V₁/T₁=V₂/T₂.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

