     LESSON 2.1 — Inorganic Substances
══════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="lesson-start" id="l2-1">
  <span class="lesson-tag lt-u2">Lesson 2.1</span>
  <h3>Properties of Inorganic Substances</h3>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h4>Classification: Acid · Base · Salt · Oxide</h4>
  <table class="ctable">
    <tr><th>Class</th><th>Definition</th><th>Strong examples</th><th>Weak examples</th></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Acid</strong></td><td>Produces H⁺ in water; donates proton</td><td>HCl, HNO₃, H₂SO₄, HClO₄, HBr, HI</td><td>CH₃COOH, H₂CO₃, HF, H₂S, H₃PO₄, HClO, HNO₂</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Base</strong></td><td>Produces OH⁻ in water; accepts proton</td><td>NaOH, KOH, Ca(OH)₂, Ba(OH)₂</td><td>NH₃·H₂O, Mg(OH)₂, Fe(OH)₂, Al(OH)₃</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Salt</strong></td><td>Metal cation + acid anion (ionic compound)</td><td>NaCl, Na₂SO₄, CaCO₃, NH₄Cl</td><td>—</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Oxide</strong></td><td>Compound of exactly two elements; one is oxygen</td><td>CO₂, SO₂, CaO, Fe₂O₃, H₂O, Na₂O</td><td>—</td></tr>
  </table>
  <div class="etip"><p>H₂O is an oxide of hydrogen (2 elements: H and O). NaOH has 3 elements → NOT an oxide, it's a base. O₂ alone is not an oxide — it's a pure element.</p></div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h4>Activity Series & Metal Reactions</h4>
  <div class="kbox kbox-green">
    <span class="kbox-label">Activity Series (Most → Least Active)</span>
    <strong>K &gt; Ca &gt; Na &gt; Mg &gt; Al &gt; Zn &gt; Fe &gt; Ni &gt; Sn &gt; Pb &gt; H &gt; Cu &gt; Hg &gt; Ag &gt; Pt &gt; Au</strong>
  </div>

  <div class="g3" style="margin-top:14px;">
    <div class="mini">
      <div class="mh">React with COLD Water</div>
      <ul>
        <li>K, Ca, Na → vigorous</li>
        <li>2Na + 2H₂O → 2NaOH + H₂↑</li>
        <li>2K + 2H₂O → 2KOH + H₂↑</li>
        <li>Mg: only with HOT water</li>
        <li>Fe, Cu: do NOT react with water</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="mini">
      <div class="mh">React with Dilute Acid → H₂</div>
      <ul>
        <li>Metals ABOVE H in series</li>
        <li>Zn + 2HCl → ZnCl₂ + H₂↑ ✓</li>
        <li>Fe + 2HCl → FeCl₂ + H₂↑ ✓</li>
        <li>Cu: does NOT react with dilute HCl</li>
        <li>Ag, Au: do NOT react with dilute acid</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="mini">
      <div class="mh">Special Cases to Know</div>
      <ul>
        <li>Fe + Cl₂ → FeCl₃ (Fe³⁺, NOT Fe²⁺)</li>
        <li>Fe + dilute HCl → FeCl₂ (Fe²⁺)</li>
        <li>Fe + CuSO₄ → FeSO₄ + Cu ✓</li>
        <li>Cu + FeSO₄: NO reaction</li>
        <li>2Na + O₂(excess) → Na₂O₂ (sodium peroxide)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="g2" style="margin-top:14px;">
    <div class="eq">
<span class="ec">— Key sodium reactions —</span>
2Na + 2H₂O → 2NaOH + H₂↑  (vigorous, floats, disappears)
4Na + O₂ → 2Na₂O           (limited O₂, room temperature)
2Na + O₂ → Na₂O₂           (excess O₂, or on heating)
Na₂O₂ + H₂O → NaOH + ½O₂  (sodium peroxide + water)
    </div>
    <div class="eq">
<span class="ec">— Key carbonate reactions —</span>
Na₂CO₃ + 2HCl → 2NaCl + H₂O + CO₂↑
2NaHCO₃ →(Δ) Na₂CO₃ + CO₂↑ + H₂O
CO₂ + Ca(OH)₂ → CaCO₃↓ + H₂O  (limewater milky)
CaCO₃ + H₂O + CO₂ → Ca(HCO₃)₂  (excess CO₂; clears)
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h4>Amphoteric Substances — React with BOTH Acid AND Base</h4>
  <div class="g2">
    <div>
      <div class="kbox kbox-purple">
        <span class="kbox-label">Al(OH)₃ — Amphoteric hydroxide</span>
        Al(OH)₃ + 3HCl → AlCl₃ + 3H₂O  (acid)<br>
        Al(OH)₃ + NaOH → NaAlO₂ + 2H₂O  (base)
      </div>
      <div class="kbox kbox-teal" style="margin-top:10px;">
        <span class="kbox-label">NaHCO₃ — Reacts with both</span>
        NaHCO₃ + HCl → NaCl + H₂O + CO₂↑  (acid)<br>
        NaHCO₃ + NaOH → Na₂CO₃ + H₂O  (base)
      </div>
    </div>
    <div>
      <div class="kbox kbox-amber">
        <span class="kbox-label">Ion Coexistence in Solutions</span>
        <strong>Acidic solution (pH &lt; 7): CANNOT have:</strong><br>
        CO₃²⁻, HCO₃⁻, OH⁻, S²⁻, SO₃²⁻, AlO₂⁻<br><br>
        <strong>Basic solution (pH &gt; 7): CANNOT have:</strong><br>
        NH₄⁺, H⁺, Mg²⁺, Cu²⁺, Fe³⁺, Al³⁺, Fe²⁺, Zn²⁺<br><br>
        <strong>Always compatible: Na⁺, K⁺, Cl⁻, NO₃⁻</strong>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ── COMMON MISTAKES 2.1 ── -->
<div class="mistake-section">
  <div class="ms-head">❌ Common Mistakes — Lesson 2.1</div>

  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "Fe reacts with Cl₂ to form FeCl₂ (iron(II) chloride)."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: 2Fe + 3Cl₂ → 2FeCl₃ (iron(III) chloride). Cl₂ is a strong oxidising agent — it oxidises Fe all the way to Fe³⁺, NOT Fe²⁺.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">Fe + dilute HCl → FeCl₂ (Fe²⁺). Fe + Cl₂ → FeCl₃ (Fe³⁺). Chlorine is stronger oxidiser than H⁺.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "Cu reacts with dilute HCl to produce H₂."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: Cu is BELOW hydrogen in the activity series → cannot displace H₂ from dilute acid. No reaction.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">Only metals ABOVE H in the activity series displace H₂ from acid. Cu, Ag, Au, Pt, Hg → no reaction with dilute HCl or H₂SO₄.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "CO₂ is an oxide, but H₂O is not."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: H₂O IS an oxide — it has exactly two elements (H and O). An oxide is any binary compound containing oxygen.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">CO₂, SO₂, NO₂, CaO, Fe₂O₃, H₂O, Na₂O are ALL oxides. NaOH is NOT an oxide (has 3 elements: Na, O, H).</div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "NaHCO₃ only reacts with acids."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: NaHCO₃ reacts with BOTH acids AND bases → it is amphoteric in the sense that it reacts with both. NaHCO₃ + NaOH → Na₂CO₃ + H₂O.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">NaHCO₃ is weakly acidic (donates H⁺ to bases) and can accept H⁺ from acids. It reacts with both.</div>
  </div>
</div>

