<div class="lesson-start" id="l2-2">
  <span class="lesson-tag lt-u2">Lesson 2.2</span>
  <h3>Basic Organic Compounds</h3>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h4>Classification of Organic Compounds</h4>
  <div class="kbox kbox-amber">
    <span class="kbox-label">Definition of Organic Compounds</span>
    Organic compounds contain <strong>C–H bonds</strong>. Treated as INORGANIC by convention: CO, CO₂, H₂CO₃, carbonates (Na₂CO₃, CaCO₃), carbides, cyanides.
  </div>

  <table class="ctable" style="margin-top:12px;">
    <tr><th>Class</th><th>General Formula</th><th>Functional Group</th><th>Key Examples</th></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Alkane</strong></td><td>CₙH₂ₙ₊₂</td><td>C–C single bonds only</td><td>CH₄ (methane), C₂H₆ (ethane), C₃H₈ (propane), C₄H₁₀ (butane)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Alkene</strong></td><td>CₙH₂ₙ</td><td>C=C double bond</td><td>C₂H₄ (ethene), C₃H₆ (propene)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Alkyne</strong></td><td>CₙH₂ₙ₋₂</td><td>C≡C triple bond</td><td>C₂H₂ (ethyne/acetylene), C₉H₁₆</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Alcohol</strong></td><td>R–OH</td><td>–OH hydroxyl</td><td>CH₃OH (methanol), C₂H₅OH (ethanol)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Carboxylic acid</strong></td><td>R–COOH</td><td>–COOH</td><td>CH₃COOH (acetic acid/ethanoic acid)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Ester</strong></td><td>R–COO–R'</td><td>–COO– ester linkage</td><td>CH₃COOC₂H₅ (ethyl acetate), CH₃COOCH₃ (methyl acetate)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Aldehyde</strong></td><td>R–CHO</td><td>–CHO</td><td>CH₃CHO (ethanal/acetaldehyde), HCHO (methanal)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Aromatic</strong></td><td>contains C₆H₅–</td><td>benzene ring</td><td>C₆H₅OH (phenol), C₆H₅CH₃ (toluene/methylbenzene)</td></tr>
  </table>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h4>Homologs — What Makes a Homologous Series</h4>
  <div class="g2">
    <div class="kbox kbox-blue">
      <span class="kbox-label">Homolog Requirements</span>
      1. Same general molecular formula (same pattern)<br>
      2. Same functional group (same reaction type)<br>
      3. Adjacent members differ by exactly <strong>CH₂</strong> (14 g/mol)<br><br>
      <strong>C₉H₁₆ homologs (CₙH₂ₙ₋₂ — alkyne/diene family):</strong><br>
      C₅H₈ ✓ (same pattern, differ by CH₂ × 4 from C₉H₁₆)<br>
      C₄H₈ ✗ (CₙH₂ₙ = alkene, different family)<br>
      C₄H₁₀ ✗ (CₙH₂ₙ₊₂ = alkane, different family)<br>
      C₈H₁₀ ✗ (CₙH₂ₙ₋₆ = aromatic, different family)
    </div>
    <div class="kbox kbox-amber">
      <span class="kbox-label">Key Reaction Types — Organic</span>
      <strong>Addition:</strong> unsaturated compound + reagent → one product<br>
      CH₂=CH₂ + Br₂ → CH₂BrCH₂Br (alkene + halogen)<br>
      CH₂=CH₂ + H₂O → CH₃CH₂OH (hydration)<br><br>
      <strong>Substitution:</strong> one atom/group replaces another<br>
      CH₄ + Cl₂ →(UV) CH₃Cl + HCl (alkane halogenation)<br>
      CH₃COOH + C₂H₅OH ⇌ CH₃COOC₂H₅ + H₂O (esterification)
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="kbox kbox-purple" style="margin-top:12px;">
    <span class="kbox-label">Phenol (C₆H₅OH) — Must Know</span>
    • <strong>FeCl₃ test:</strong> phenol + FeCl₃ → <strong>purple/violet colour</strong> ✓ (identification test for phenol)<br>
    • Phenol + Br₂ water → white precipitate (2,4,6-tribromophenol) — this is a <strong>substitution</strong>, NOT addition<br>
    • Phenol + NaOH → sodium phenoxide (phenol is weakly acidic)<br>
    • Phenol is a <strong>WEAKER acid</strong> than CH₃COOH (Ka phenol ~10⁻¹⁰ vs Ka acetic ~1.8×10⁻⁵)<br>
    • Phenol does NOT "extract" Br₂ from bromine water — it reacts with it
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ── COMMON MISTAKES 2.2 ── -->
<div class="mistake-section">
  <div class="ms-head">❌ Common Mistakes — Lesson 2.2</div>

  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "CO₂ is an organic compound because it contains carbon."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: CO₂ is treated as INORGANIC by convention. Organic compounds need C–H bonds. CO₂ has no hydrogen bonded to carbon.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">Inorganic carbon compounds: CO, CO₂, H₂CO₃, carbonates, carbides. All others with C–H bonds = organic.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "C₄H₈ is a homolog of C₉H₁₆."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: C₉H₁₆ follows CₙH₂ₙ₋₂ (alkyne/diene series). C₄H₈ follows CₙH₂ₙ (alkene series). Different functional groups → NOT homologs.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">Homologs must have the SAME functional group AND same general formula. C₅H₈ is a homolog of C₉H₁₆ (both CₙH₂ₙ₋₂).</div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "Phenol is a stronger acid than acetic acid because it reacts with NaOH."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: Phenol is a WEAKER acid than acetic acid. Ka(phenol) ≈ 10⁻¹⁰, Ka(acetic) ≈ 1.8×10⁻⁵. Acetic acid is about 100,000× stronger.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">Both phenol and acetic acid react with NaOH, but that doesn't tell you which is stronger. Use Ka values to compare acid strength.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "Benzene reacts with Cl₂ to give an addition reaction."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: Benzene + Cl₂ (with FeCl₃ catalyst) → SUBSTITUTION (C₆H₅Cl + HCl). The benzene ring is preserved. Addition occurs only with H₂ under special conditions.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">Benzene ring is very stable — prefers substitution over addition. Alkenes prefer addition.</div>
  </div>
</div>

