<div class="lesson-start" id="l2-3">
  <span class="lesson-tag lt-u2">Lesson 2.3</span>
  <h3>Oxidation-Reduction (Redox) Reactions</h3>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h4>Oxidation States & Rules</h4>
  <div class="g2">
    <div>
      <div class="kbox kbox-green">
        <span class="kbox-label">Oxidation State Rules</span>
        1. Free elements: oxidation state = 0<br>
        2. O is usually −2 (except H₂O₂: O=−1; OF₂: O=+2)<br>
        3. H is usually +1 (except metal hydrides: H=−1, e.g. NaH)<br>
        4. F is always −1<br>
        5. Group IA metals: always +1 (Na, K, Li)<br>
        6. Group IIA metals: always +2 (Mg, Ca, Ba)<br>
        7. Sum = overall charge of species
      </div>
    </div>
    <div>
      <table class="ctable">
        <tr><th>Compound</th><th>Element</th><th>Oxidation State</th></tr>
        <tr><td>NaClO₃</td><td>Cl</td><td>+5 (Na=+1, 3O=−6: Cl=+5)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>NaClO₄</td><td>Cl</td><td>+7 (Na=+1, 4O=−8: Cl=+7)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>NaClO</td><td>Cl</td><td>+1 (Na=+1, O=−2: Cl=+1)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>CaCl₂</td><td>Cl</td><td>−1</td></tr>
        <tr><td>H₂O₂</td><td>O</td><td>−1 (unusual!)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>NH₄NO₃</td><td>N (NH₄⁺)</td><td>−3</td></tr>
        <tr><td>NH₄NO₃</td><td>N (NO₃⁻)</td><td>+5</td></tr>
      </table>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="g2" style="margin-top:14px;">
    <div class="kbox kbox-red">
      <span class="kbox-label">Oxidising Agent</span>
      Gets <strong>REDUCED</strong> (gains e⁻, oxidation state decreases)<br>
      Examples: O₂, Cl₂, F₂, KMnO₄, H₂SO₄(conc), HNO₃, Fe³⁺, MnO₂, H₂O₂
    </div>
    <div class="kbox kbox-blue">
      <span class="kbox-label">Reducing Agent</span>
      Gets <strong>OXIDISED</strong> (loses e⁻, oxidation state increases)<br>
      Examples: H₂, CO, C, metals (Na, Fe, Zn, Al), Fe²⁺, SO₂, HI, HBr
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="etip"><p>H₂SO₄(conc) as oxidising agent: S + 2H₂SO₄(conc) → 3SO₂ + 2H₂O. S goes 0→+4 (oxidised); S in H₂SO₄ goes +6→+4 (reduced). This is oxidising acid. Dilute H₂SO₄ + Zn → ZnSO₄ + H₂: H⁺ is reduced (0 in H₂), H₂SO₄ acts only as an acid here, NOT as oxidising agent.</p></div>
</div>

<!-- ── COMMON MISTAKES 2.3 ── -->
<div class="mistake-section">
  <div class="ms-head">❌ Common Mistakes — Lesson 2.3</div>

  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "HCl + NaOH → NaCl + H₂O is a redox reaction."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: Neutralisation is NOT a redox reaction. No oxidation states change: H stays +1, Cl stays −1, Na stays +1, O stays −2.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">To identify redox: check if ANY element changes oxidation state. If not → not redox.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "In NaClO₃, Cl has oxidation state +3."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: In NaClO₃: Na=+1, O×3=−6, total=0 → Cl = 0−(1)−(−6) = +5. Cl = +5.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">Always use the sum rule: sum of all oxidation states = overall charge. Here: +1 + Cl + 3(−2) = 0 → Cl = +5.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "The oxidising agent gets oxidised."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: The OXIDISING agent gets REDUCED (gains electrons, oxidation state decreases). The REDUCING agent gets OXIDISED.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">Memory aid: Oxidising agent → oxidises OTHERS → itself gets reduced. OIL RIG: Oxidation Is Loss, Reduction Is Gain (of electrons).</div>
  </div>
</div>

