     LESSON 2.4 — Ionic Reactions & Testing
══════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="lesson-start" id="l2-4">
  <span class="lesson-tag lt-u2">Lesson 2.4</span>
  <h3>Ionic Reactions & Testing Methods</h3>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h4>Rules for Writing Ionic Equations</h4>
  <div class="g2">
    <div class="kbox kbox-green">
      <span class="kbox-label">WRITE as ions (split up)</span>
      Strong acids: HCl, H₂SO₄, HNO₃, HBr, HI, HClO₄<br>
      Strong bases: NaOH, KOH, Ca(OH)₂, Ba(OH)₂<br>
      Soluble salts: NaCl, Na₂SO₄, KNO₃, etc.<br><br>
      So: HCl → H⁺ + Cl⁻ &nbsp;|&nbsp; NaOH → Na⁺ + OH⁻<br>
      Na₂SO₄ → 2Na⁺ + SO₄²⁻
    </div>
    <div class="kbox kbox-red">
      <span class="kbox-label">DO NOT split — write as formula</span>
      Weak acids: CH₃COOH, H₂CO₃, H₂S, HF, HNO₂, HClO<br>
      Weak bases: NH₃·H₂O, Fe(OH)₂, Al(OH)₃, Mg(OH)₂<br>
      Precipitates: BaSO₄↓, AgCl↓, CaCO₃↓, Fe(OH)₃↓<br>
      Gases: CO₂↑, H₂↑, NH₃↑<br>
      Water: H₂O<br>
      Oxides, pure liquids, pure solids
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="eq" style="margin-top:14px;">
<span class="ec">Correct ionic equations</span>
HCl + NaOH → NaCl + H₂O     becomes: H⁺ + OH⁻ → H₂O
BaCl₂ + H₂SO₄ → BaSO₄↓ + 2HCl  becomes: Ba²⁺ + SO₄²⁻ → BaSO₄↓
Na₂CO₃ + 2HCl → 2NaCl + H₂O + CO₂↑  becomes: CO₃²⁻ + 2H⁺ → CO₂↑ + H₂O
AgNO₃ + HCl → AgCl↓ + HNO₃  becomes: Ag⁺ + Cl⁻ → AgCl↓
  </div>

  <div class="etip"><p>WRONG: "Cu + 2H⁺ → Cu²⁺ + H₂↑". Cu is below H in activity series — it cannot displace H₂ from dilute acid. This is an invalid ionic equation!</p></div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h4>Ion Testing Methods — The Complete Reference</h4>
  <table class="ctable">
    <tr><th>Ion</th><th>Reagent</th><th>Observation</th><th>Equation</th></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Cl⁻</strong></td><td>AgNO₃ + dilute HNO₃</td><td>White precipitate, insoluble in dilute HNO₃</td><td>Ag⁺ + Cl⁻ → AgCl↓</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>SO₄²⁻</strong></td><td>BaCl₂ + dilute HCl</td><td>White precipitate, insoluble in dilute HCl</td><td>Ba²⁺ + SO₄²⁻ → BaSO₄↓</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>CO₃²⁻</strong></td><td>Dilute HCl, then bubble through Ca(OH)₂</td><td>Effervescence; limewater turns milky</td><td>CO₃²⁻ + 2H⁺ → CO₂↑ + H₂O; CO₂ + Ca(OH)₂ → CaCO₃↓</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>NH₄⁺</strong></td><td>NaOH (heat); damp red litmus</td><td>Pungent smell; red litmus turns blue</td><td>NH₄⁺ + OH⁻ → NH₃↑ + H₂O</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Fe³⁺</strong></td><td>KSCN solution</td><td>Blood-red colour</td><td>Fe³⁺ + SCN⁻ → [Fe(SCN)]²⁺</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Fe²⁺</strong></td><td>NaOH; expose to air</td><td>Dirty green ppt → turns rusty brown</td><td>Fe²⁺+2OH⁻→Fe(OH)₂↓; 4Fe(OH)₂+O₂+2H₂O→4Fe(OH)₃↓</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Cu²⁺</strong></td><td>NaOH</td><td>Pale blue precipitate</td><td>Cu²⁺ + 2OH⁻ → Cu(OH)₂↓</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Na⁺ / K⁺</strong></td><td>Flame test</td><td>Na→yellow; K→purple (through blue cobalt glass)</td><td>—</td></tr>
  </table>

  <div class="etip" style="margin-top:14px;"><p>
    For <strong>Cl⁻ test</strong>: use AgNO₃ + dilute HNO₃ (NOT H₂SO₄ which adds SO₄²⁻ interference; NOT BaCl₂ which itself contains Cl⁻!).<br>
    For <strong>SO₄²⁻ test</strong>: acidify first with dilute HCl (to remove CO₃²⁻ and SO₃²⁻ which also form white precipitates with Ba²⁺). Then add BaCl₂.<br>
    <strong>Blue cobalt glass</strong> for K flame test: filters out yellow light from Na impurities, revealing K's purple flame.
  </p></div>
</div>

<!-- ── COMMON MISTAKES 2.4 ── -->
<div class="mistake-section">
  <div class="ms-head">❌ Common Mistakes — Lesson 2.4</div>

  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "Use BaCl₂ to test for Cl⁻ ions."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: BaCl₂ contains Cl⁻ — you can't test for Cl⁻ using a reagent that already has Cl⁻! Use AgNO₃ + dilute HNO₃ for the Cl⁻ test.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">BaCl₂ is used to test for SO₄²⁻ (forms BaSO₄↓). AgNO₃ is used for Cl⁻ (forms AgCl↓).</div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "AgNO₃ + dilute H₂SO₄ is used to test for Cl⁻."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: Using H₂SO₄ introduces SO₄²⁻ which can form Ag₂SO₄ (slightly soluble) — this interferes with the test. Always use dilute HNO₃ to acidify for the Cl⁻ test.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">Dilute HNO₃ does not precipitate with Ag⁺, so it doesn't interfere. It eliminates other anions (CO₃²⁻, SO₃²⁻) that would give false positives.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "Bubble CO₂ into BaCl₂ solution to test for CO₂."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: CO₂ does NOT precipitate directly with BaCl₂. Test for CO₂ by bubbling through Ca(OH)₂ (limewater) → CaCO₃↓ (milky).</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">BaCl₂ is acidic enough that BaCO₃ does not form directly from CO₂. Ca(OH)₂ is the correct reagent for CO₂.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "Cobalt blue glass filters out the purple light of potassium."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: Cobalt blue glass filters out the YELLOW light of SODIUM. It allows the purple light of potassium to pass through so you can see it.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">Na gives a very strong yellow flame that masks K's purple. Cobalt glass absorbs yellow, revealing the purple/violet from K.</div>
