<div class="summary-section" id="ch2-summary">
  <div class="sum-head">📌 Chapter 2 Summary — What You MUST Own</div>
  <div class="must-own-grid">
    <div class="must-item">
      <div class="mi-title">1. Acid/Base/Salt/Oxide</div>
      <div class="mi-body">H₂O = oxide of H. NaOH = base (3 elements, not oxide). Strong acids: HCl, HNO₃, H₂SO₄. Weak acids: CH₃COOH, H₂CO₃, HClO. Strong bases: NaOH, KOH, Ca(OH)₂. Weak bases: NH₃·H₂O.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="must-item">
      <div class="mi-title">2. Activity Series</div>
      <div class="mi-body">K&gt;Ca&gt;Na&gt;Mg&gt;Al&gt;Zn&gt;Fe&gt;…&gt;H&gt;Cu&gt;Ag&gt;Au. Metals above H → react with dilute acid to give H₂. Cu, Ag, Au → do NOT react with dilute HCl. Na reacts with cold water.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="must-item">
      <div class="mi-title">3. Fe + Cl₂ → FeCl₃ (NOT FeCl₂)</div>
      <div class="mi-body">Cl₂ is a strong enough oxidiser to push Fe all the way to +3 state. Fe + dilute HCl → FeCl₂ (+2). Fe + Cl₂ → FeCl₃ (+3). This distinction appears on every exam.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="must-item">
      <div class="mi-title">4. Organic Compound Classes</div>
      <div class="mi-body">Alkane CₙH₂ₙ₊₂, Alkene CₙH₂ₙ, Alkyne CₙH₂ₙ₋₂. Alcohol –OH, Acid –COOH, Ester –COO–, Aldehyde –CHO. Homologs: same functional group + same formula pattern + differ by CH₂.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="must-item">
      <div class="mi-title">5. Phenol Tests</div>
      <div class="mi-body">FeCl₃ → purple colour (identification). Bromine water → white precipitate (substitution, NOT addition). Phenol is WEAKER acid than acetic acid. Phenol + NaOH → sodium phenoxide.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="must-item">
      <div class="mi-title">6. Oxidation States</div>
      <div class="mi-body">O usually −2. H usually +1. F always −1. NaClO₃: Cl=+5. NaClO₄: Cl=+7. NaClO: Cl=+1. NH₄NO₃: N is −3 (in NH₄⁺) and +5 (in NO₃⁻). Sum = overall charge.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="must-item">
      <div class="mi-title">7. Ion Testing</div>
      <div class="mi-body">Cl⁻: AgNO₃ + dilute HNO₃ → white AgCl↓. SO₄²⁻: BaCl₂ + dilute HCl → white BaSO₄↓. NH₄⁺: NaOH + heat → NH₃ (red litmus turns blue). Fe³⁺: KSCN → blood red. Fe²⁺: NaOH → dirty green → rusty brown in air.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="must-item">
      <div class="mi-title">8. Ionic Equations</div>
      <div class="mi-body">Split: strong acids, strong bases, soluble salts. Keep as formula: weak acids/bases, precipitates, gases, water. Cu + 2H⁺ → Cu²⁺ + H₂ is WRONG (Cu below H in activity series). O²⁻ doesn't exist in aqueous solution.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

