<!-- ═══════════════════════════
     LESSON 3.1 — Atomic Structure & Periodic Law
═══════════════════════════ -->
<div class="lesson-start" id="l3-1">
  <span class="lesson-tag lt-u3">Lesson 3.1</span>
  <h3>Atomic Structure & Periodic Law</h3>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h4>Inside the Atom</h4>
  <div class="g2">
    <div>
      <div class="kbox kbox-purple">
        <span class="kbox-label">Atomic Number & Mass Number</span>
        <strong>Atomic number (Z)</strong> = number of protons = number of electrons (neutral atom)<br>
        <strong>Mass number (A)</strong> = protons + neutrons<br>
        <strong>Neutrons</strong> = A − Z<br><br>
        Example: ¹⁴₆C → Z=6 (protons=6), A=14, neutrons=14−6=8
      </div>
      <div class="kbox kbox-blue" style="margin-top:10px;">
        <span class="kbox-label">Electron Shell Filling (Bohr Model)</span>
        Shell capacity: K=2, L=8, M=18 (but fills to 8 before starting M for periods 2 & 3)<br>
        Fill innermost first, outermost = valence electrons<br><br>
        Na (Z=11): 2, 8, 1 → 1 valence electron → Group IA<br>
        Cl (Z=17): 2, 8, 7 → 7 valence electrons → Group VIIA<br>
        Ar (Z=18): 2, 8, 8 → noble gas (full outer shell)
      </div>
    </div>
    <div>
      <table class="ctable">
        <tr><th>Z</th><th>Element</th><th>Shell Config</th><th>Orbital Config</th></tr>
        <tr><td>6</td><td>C</td><td>2,4</td><td>1s²2s²2p²</td></tr>
        <tr><td>7</td><td>N</td><td>2,5</td><td>1s²2s²2p³</td></tr>
        <tr><td>8</td><td>O</td><td>2,6</td><td>1s²2s²2p⁴</td></tr>
        <tr><td>9</td><td>F</td><td>2,7</td><td>1s²2s²2p⁵</td></tr>
        <tr><td>11</td><td>Na</td><td>2,8,1</td><td>…3s¹</td></tr>
        <tr><td>15</td><td>P</td><td>2,8,5</td><td>…3s²3p³</td></tr>
        <tr><td>16</td><td>S</td><td>2,8,6</td><td>…3s²3p⁴</td></tr>
        <tr><td>17</td><td>Cl</td><td>2,8,7</td><td>…3s²3p⁵</td></tr>
        <tr><td>18</td><td>Ar</td><td>2,8,8</td><td>…3s²3p⁶</td></tr>
        <tr><td>19</td><td>K</td><td>2,8,8,1</td><td>…<strong>4s¹</strong> ← not 3d¹!</td></tr>
        <tr><td>20</td><td>Ca</td><td>2,8,8,2</td><td>…4s²</td></tr>
      </table>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="etip"><p><strong>K (Z=19)</strong> fills 4s¹ (NOT 3d¹). The 4s orbital fills before 3d. This is one of the most common exam traps for electron configuration questions. Correct: 1s²2s²2p⁶3s²3p⁶<strong>4s¹</strong>.</p></div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h4>Periodic Law & Trends</h4>
  <div class="g2">
    <div>
      <div class="kbox kbox-amber">
        <span class="kbox-label">Across a Period (left → right, same period)</span>
        Atomic radius: <strong>decreases ←→ smaller</strong> (more protons pull e⁻ closer)<br>
        Ionisation energy: <strong>increases →</strong> (harder to remove electron)<br>
        Electronegativity: <strong>increases →</strong><br>
        Metallic character: <strong>decreases →</strong><br>
        Non-metallic character: <strong>increases →</strong><br>
        Acidity of oxides: <strong>increases →</strong> (Na₂O basic → SO₃ acidic)
      </div>
    </div>
    <div>
      <div class="kbox kbox-teal">
        <span class="kbox-label">Down a Group (top → bottom, same group)</span>
        Atomic radius: <strong>increases ↓</strong> (more electron shells)<br>
        Ionisation energy: <strong>decreases ↓</strong><br>
        Electronegativity: <strong>decreases ↓</strong><br>
        Metallic character: <strong>increases ↓</strong><br>
        Acid strength of hydrides: <strong>increases ↓</strong> (HF&lt;HCl&lt;HBr&lt;HI)<br>
        Stability of hydrides: <strong>decreases ↓</strong>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <table class="ctable" style="margin-top:12px;">
    <tr><th>Trend</th><th>Period 3 (Na→Cl)</th><th>Group IA (Li→Cs)</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Atomic radius</td><td>Na&gt;Mg&gt;Al&gt;Si&gt;P&gt;S&gt;Cl (decreases)</td><td>Li&lt;Na&lt;K&lt;Rb&lt;Cs (increases)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Ionisation energy</td><td>Na&lt;Mg&lt;Al&lt;Si&lt;P&lt;S&lt;Cl (increases)</td><td>Li&gt;Na&gt;K&gt;Rb&gt;Cs (decreases)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Metal reactivity</td><td>Na&gt;Mg&gt;Al (most → least active)</td><td>Li&lt;Na&lt;K&lt;Rb&lt;Cs (increases)</td></tr>
  </table>
  <div class="etip"><p><strong>Smallest atomic radius:</strong> Fluorine (F, Z=9) has the smallest radius of all elements — highest nuclear charge for its period, very small shell. <strong>Largest:</strong> Cs (caesium) among the first 20 elements, K is the largest.</p></div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h4>Finding Period & Group from Z</h4>
  <div class="g2">
    <div class="kbox kbox-green">
      <span class="kbox-label">Period</span>
      = number of electron shells occupied<br><br>
      Z=1-2: Period 1 (1 shell)<br>
      Z=3-10: Period 2 (2 shells)<br>
      Z=11-18: Period 3 (3 shells)<br>
      Z=19-20 (and 21-36): Period 4 (4 shells)
    </div>
    <div class="kbox kbox-purple">
      <span class="kbox-label">Group (main groups only)</span>
      = number of valence electrons<br><br>
      1 valence e⁻ → Group IA (Na, K, Li)<br>
      2 valence e⁻ → Group IIA (Mg, Ca)<br>
      6 valence e⁻ → Group VIA (O, S)<br>
      7 valence e⁻ → Group VIIA (F, Cl) — halogens<br>
      8 valence e⁻ → Group 0 (Ne, Ar) — noble gases<br><br>
      Period 2, Group VIIA = <strong>Fluorine (F)</strong><br>
      Period 3, Group VIA = <strong>Sulfur (S)</strong><br>
      Period 3, Group VA = <strong>Phosphorus (P)</strong>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- COMMON MISTAKES 3.1 -->
<div class="mistake-section">
  <div class="ms-head">❌ Common Mistakes — Lesson 3.1</div>
  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "Potassium (Z=19) has electron configuration ending in 3d¹."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: K ends in <strong>4s¹</strong>. The 4s subshell fills before 3d. Full config: 1s²2s²2p⁶3s²3p⁶<strong>4s¹</strong>.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">This is tested directly in Jan 2026 Q45. Aufbau principle: 4s has lower energy than 3d, so it fills first.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "Fluorine has a larger atomic radius than oxygen because it has more electrons."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: F is smaller than O. Both are in period 2; F has higher nuclear charge (Z=9 vs O's Z=8), pulling electrons closer → smaller radius.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">Going across a period: atomic radius decreases because nuclear charge increases while the shell number stays the same.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "Phosphorus (P) has outermost electron configuration 3s²3p²."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: P has Z=15 and is in Group VA (5 valence electrons). Outer config: <strong>3s²3p³</strong> (5 electrons in the M shell).</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">3s²3p² gives only 4 valence electrons → that's Silicon (Si, Z=14). Phosphorus has one more: 3s²3p³.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "The second period, Group VIIA element is Chlorine."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: Period 2, Group VIIA = <strong>Fluorine (F)</strong>. Chlorine is Period 3, Group VIIA.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">Period 2 elements: Li, Be, B, C, N, O, F, Ne (Z=3 to 10). Cl is Z=17, which is Period 3.</div>
  </div>
</div>

