  <h3>Chemical Bonds & Intermolecular Forces</h3>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h4>Three Types of Chemical Bonds</h4>
  <div class="g3">
    <div class="mini">
      <div class="mh">Ionic Bond</div>
      <ul>
        <li>Metal + non-metal → electron transfer</li>
        <li>Electrostatic attraction between ions</li>
        <li>High melting point</li>
        <li>Conducts when molten or dissolved</li>
        <li>NaCl, KCl, MgO, CaO, Na₂O, NaOH, CaCl₂, Na₂SO₄, NH₄Cl</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="mini">
      <div class="mh">Covalent Bond</div>
      <ul>
        <li>Non-metal + non-metal → shared electrons</li>
        <li>Single: H–H, Cl–Cl, H–Cl</li>
        <li>Double: O=O, C=O (in CO₂)</li>
        <li>Triple: N≡N</li>
        <li>Polar: HCl, H₂O, NH₃, HF</li>
        <li>Non-polar: H₂, Cl₂, N₂, O₂, CH₄</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="mini">
      <div class="mh">Both Ionic + Covalent</div>
      <ul>
        <li>Compounds with polyatomic ions</li>
        <li>NaOH: ionic Na⁺–OH⁻ + covalent O–H</li>
        <li>Na₂SO₄: ionic + covalent S–O in SO₄²⁻</li>
        <li>NH₄Cl: ionic NH₄⁺–Cl⁻ + covalent N–H</li>
        <li>Na₂O₂: ionic + peroxide O–O covalent</li>
        <li>NaHCO₃: ionic + covalent (CO₃²⁻ has covalent bonds)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="kbox kbox-amber" style="margin-top:14px;">
    <span class="kbox-label">EXAM TRAP — Identifying Bond Types</span>
    "Which pair of substances have the SAME type of bonding?"<br>
    ✓ H₂ and Cl₂: both non-polar covalent only ✓<br>
    ✓ NaCl and KCl: both ionic only ✓<br>
    ✗ NaOH and KCl: NaOH = ionic+covalent; KCl = ionic only — DIFFERENT ✗<br>
    ✗ HNO₃ and NaNO₃: HNO₃ = only covalent; NaNO₃ = ionic+covalent — DIFFERENT ✗<br>
    ✓ NH₄Cl and NaOH: both contain ionic AND covalent bonds ✓
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h4>Intermolecular Forces</h4>
  <div class="g2">
    <div>
      <div class="kbox kbox-blue">
        <span class="kbox-label">Types (weakest → strongest)</span>
        1. Van der Waals forces (all molecules)<br>
        2. Dipole-dipole forces (polar molecules)<br>
        3. Hydrogen bonds (N–H, O–H, F–H with lone pairs)<br><br>
        Stronger intermolecular forces → higher boiling/melting point<br><br>
        H₂O has anomalously high bp (100°C) because of strong O–H···O hydrogen bonds
      </div>
    </div>
    <div>
      <div class="kbox kbox-teal">
        <span class="kbox-label">Hydrogen Bonding Examples</span>
        H₂O (water): O–H···O very strong<br>
        HF: F–H···F strong<br>
        NH₃: N–H···N moderate<br>
        CH₄: NO hydrogen bonds (C–H not polar enough)<br><br>
        Boiling point comparison:<br>
        H₂O &gt; HF &gt; NH₃ &gt; CH₄<br>
        (despite H₂O having lower molar mass than HF and NH₃)
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

