<div class="lesson-start" id="l3-3">
  <span class="lesson-tag lt-u3">Lesson 3.3</span>
  <h3>Reaction Rate</h3>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h4>Calculating Reaction Rate</h4>
  <div class="g2">
    <div>
      <div class="kbox kbox-purple">
        <span class="kbox-label">Formula</span>
        <strong>v = Δc / Δt</strong><br>
        v = reaction rate (mol·L⁻¹·s⁻¹ or mol·L⁻¹·min⁻¹)<br>
        Δc = change in concentration (mol·L⁻¹)<br>
        Δt = time interval (s or min)<br><br>
        Rate ratios = stoichiometric ratios:<br>
        For aA + bB → cC + dD:<br>
        v(A):v(B):v(C):v(D) = a:b:c:d
      </div>
    </div>
    <div>
      <div class="kbox kbox-amber">
        <span class="kbox-label">Worked Example</span>
        2SO₂ + O₂ → 2SO₃ in a 2 L container.<br>
        SO₂ decreases by 0.4 mol in 10 s.<br><br>
        Δ[SO₂] = 0.4/2 = 0.2 mol/L<br>
        v(SO₂) = 0.2/10 = <strong>0.02 mol·L⁻¹·s⁻¹</strong><br><br>
        Ratio: v(SO₂):v(O₂):v(SO₃) = 2:1:2<br>
        v(O₂) = ½ × v(SO₂) = <strong>0.01 mol·L⁻¹·s⁻¹</strong><br>
        v(SO₃) = v(SO₂) = <strong>0.02 mol·L⁻¹·s⁻¹</strong>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h4>Factors Affecting Reaction Rate</h4>
  <table class="ctable">
    <tr><th>Factor</th><th>Effect on Rate</th><th>Explanation</th></tr>
    <tr><td>↑ Temperature</td><td>↑ Rate (significantly)</td><td>More particles exceed activation energy; ~doubles per 10°C rise</td></tr>
    <tr><td>↑ Concentration</td><td>↑ Rate</td><td>More particles per unit volume → more frequent collisions</td></tr>
    <tr><td>↑ Pressure (gas)</td><td>↑ Rate</td><td>Equivalent to increasing concentration for gases</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Catalyst</td><td>↑ Rate (both directions equally)</td><td>Lowers activation energy; does NOT shift equilibrium position</td></tr>
    <tr><td>↑ Surface area</td><td>↑ Rate</td><td>Powder reacts faster than block — more exposed surface</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Light (UV)</td><td>↑ Rate (photochemical)</td><td>e.g. CH₄ + Cl₂ → CH₃Cl + HCl (only in UV light)</td></tr>
  </table>
  <div class="etip"><p>A catalyst speeds up BOTH forward and reverse reactions by the <em>same factor</em>. It does NOT shift the equilibrium position — it only helps the system reach equilibrium faster. This is tested every exam!</p></div>
</div>

<!-- COMMON MISTAKES 3.3 -->
<div class="mistake-section">
  <div class="ms-head">❌ Common Mistakes — Lesson 3.3</div>
  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "Adding a catalyst shifts the equilibrium to produce more product."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: A catalyst does NOT shift equilibrium. It increases both forward and reverse rates equally → reaches the same equilibrium position faster.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">To shift equilibrium, you need to change concentration, temperature, or pressure — not a catalyst.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "Reaction rate for 2A → 3B: v(A) = v(B) because both are in the same reaction."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: v(A):v(B) = 2:3 (stoichiometric ratio). If v(A)=0.02 mol/L/s, then v(B) = 0.03 mol/L/s.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">Rates are proportional to stoichiometric coefficients. Always compare rates using the mole ratio from the balanced equation.</div>
  </div>
</div>

