<!-- ═══════════════════════════
     LESSON 3.4 — Chemical Equilibrium
═══════════════════════════ -->
<div class="lesson-start" id="l3-4">
  <span class="lesson-tag lt-u3">Lesson 3.4</span>
  <h3>Chemical Equilibrium</h3>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h4>What Is Equilibrium?</h4>
  <div class="kbox kbox-purple">
    <span class="kbox-label">The ONE definition that is always true</span>
    At equilibrium: <strong>forward rate = reverse rate</strong><br>
    Concentrations of all species remain <strong>constant</strong> (not necessarily equal).<br>
    The reaction continues in BOTH directions — it is dynamic, not stopped.<br><br>
    ✓ Concentrations are constant → equilibrium indicator<br>
    ✗ Concentrations are equal → NOT necessarily true<br>
    ✗ Reverse rate = 0 → that would mean the reaction stopped, not equilibrium
  </div>

  <div class="etip" style="margin-top:14px;"><p>
    The question "what is always equal at equilibrium?" has ONE answer: <strong>forward rate = reverse rate</strong>. Concentration of reactants ≠ products (depends on Kc). Mass of reactants ≠ products (usually). Mole ratio ≠ stoichiometric ratio (depends on initial conditions).
  </p></div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h4>Le Chatelier's Principle</h4>
  <div class="kbox kbox-amber">
    <span class="kbox-label">Principle</span>
    When a system at equilibrium is disturbed, it shifts to <strong>partially oppose</strong> the disturbance.
  </div>
  <table class="ctable" style="margin-top:12px;">
    <tr><th>Disturbance</th><th>Shift direction</th><th>Rule</th></tr>
    <tr><td>↑ [reactant]</td><td>→ Forward (right)</td><td>Consumes added reactant</td></tr>
    <tr><td>↑ [product]</td><td>← Reverse (left)</td><td>Consumes added product</td></tr>
    <tr><td>↑ Temperature</td><td>→ Endothermic direction</td><td>Absorbs added heat</td></tr>
    <tr><td>↓ Temperature</td><td>→ Exothermic direction</td><td>Produces heat to compensate</td></tr>
    <tr><td>↑ Pressure</td><td>→ Side with fewer gas moles</td><td>Reduces total pressure</td></tr>
    <tr><td>↓ Pressure</td><td>→ Side with more gas moles</td><td>Increases total pressure</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Add inert gas (const V)</td><td>No shift</td><td>Partial pressures unchanged</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Add catalyst</td><td>No shift</td><td>Reaches equilibrium faster only</td></tr>
  </table>

  <div class="kbox kbox-blue" style="margin-top:14px;">
    <span class="kbox-label">Key Exam Examples — 3 Reactions You Must Know</span>
    <strong>1) N₂ + 3H₂ ⇌ 2NH₃ (exothermic, gas moles: 4→2)</strong><br>
    High pressure → right (fewer gas moles). Low T → right (exothermic favoured). Catalyst → no shift.<br>
    Adding Ar at constant volume → NO shift (partial pressures of N₂, H₂, NH₃ unchanged).<br><br>
    <strong>2) C(s) + H₂O(g) ⇌ CO(g) + H₂(g) (endothermic, gas moles: 1→2)</strong><br>
    To shift REVERSE: decrease T (opposes endothermic) AND increase P (fewer gas moles on left). Both → reverse.<br><br>
    <strong>3) 2HI(g) ⇌ H₂(g) + I₂(g) (equal gas moles: 2→2)</strong><br>
    Changing pressure: NO shift (same gas moles both sides). Increasing T (endothermic reverse) → shifts left.
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h4>Valid vs Invalid Equilibrium Indicators</h4>
  <div class="g2">
    <div class="kbox kbox-green">
      <span class="kbox-label">✓ VALID equilibrium indicators</span>
      • All concentrations are constant (unchanging)<br>
      • v(forward, species A) = v(reverse, species A)<br>
      • Colour no longer changing (if coloured species present)<br>
      • Total pressure no longer changing (variable-volume system)
    </div>
    <div class="kbox kbox-red">
      <span class="kbox-label">✗ NOT valid equilibrium indicators</span>
      • "v(A, forward) = v(B, forward)" — rates of different species in same direction are just stoichiometry, always true<br>
      • "[reactant] = [product]" — depends on Kc, not a general condition<br>
      • "Mole ratio = stoichiometric ratio" — could just be the initial condition<br>
      • "Reaction has stopped" — equilibrium is dynamic!
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="etip"><p>
    For N₂ + 3H₂ ⇌ 2NH₃:<br>
    ✗ "v(N₂ consumed) = ½ × v(H₂ consumed)" — this is just stoichiometry (1:3 ratio), always true, NOT an equilibrium indicator.<br>
    ✓ "v(N₂ consumed) = v(N₂ produced)" — same species, opposite directions → valid equilibrium indicator.
  </p></div>
</div>

<!-- COMMON MISTAKES 3.4 -->
<div class="mistake-section">
  <div class="ms-head">❌ Common Mistakes — Lesson 3.4</div>
  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "Adding Ar (inert gas) at constant volume shifts the equilibrium."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: At constant volume, adding Ar increases total pressure but does NOT change the partial pressures of any reactant or product. Concentrations are unchanged → NO equilibrium shift.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">Equilibrium shifts when the concentration (or partial pressure) of a reactant or product changes. Inert gas at constant volume doesn't affect any of these.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "At equilibrium, concentrations of reactants equal concentrations of products."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: At equilibrium, concentrations are CONSTANT, but they are NOT necessarily equal. The ratio is determined by the equilibrium constant Kc.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">Example: N₂ + 3H₂ ⇌ 2NH₃. At equilibrium in the Haber process, [NH₃] is much less than [N₂] and [H₂] — they are definitely not equal.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "Decreasing temperature always shifts equilibrium to the right."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: Decreasing temperature shifts equilibrium toward the EXOTHERMIC direction. If the forward reaction is endothermic (like C+H₂O⇌CO+H₂), then DECREASING T shifts it LEFT (reverse).</div>
