<div class="lesson-start" id="l3-5">
  <span class="lesson-tag lt-u3">Lesson 3.5</span>
  <h3>Electrolyte Solutions & Theories</h3>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h4>Electrolytes vs Non-Electrolytes</h4>
  <div class="kbox kbox-blue">
    <span class="kbox-label">Definitions</span>
    <strong>Electrolyte:</strong> a compound that conducts electricity when dissolved in water or when melted — it ionises in solution.<br>
    <strong>Non-electrolyte:</strong> a compound that does NOT ionise in water — no free ions formed.
  </div>
  <div class="g2" style="margin-top:12px;">
    <table class="ctable">
      <tr><th>Strong Electrolytes (fully ionise)</th><th>Ionisation</th></tr>
      <tr><td>HCl (strong acid)</td><td>HCl → H⁺ + Cl⁻ (one arrow →)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>HNO₃, H₂SO₄ (strong acids)</td><td>Complete ionisation</td></tr>
      <tr><td>NaOH, KOH, Ca(OH)₂ (strong bases)</td><td>NaOH → Na⁺ + OH⁻</td></tr>
      <tr><td>NaCl, Na₂SO₄, KNO₃ (soluble salts)</td><td>NaCl → Na⁺ + Cl⁻</td></tr>
    </table>
    <table class="ctable">
      <tr><th>Weak Electrolytes (partial ionisation)</th><th>Ionisation</th></tr>
      <tr><td>CH₃COOH (weak acid)</td><td>CH₃COOH ⇌ CH₃COO⁻ + H⁺ (⇌)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>NH₃·H₂O (weak base)</td><td>NH₃·H₂O ⇌ NH₄⁺ + OH⁻</td></tr>
      <tr><td>H₂CO₃, HF, H₂S (weak acids)</td><td>Partial, reversible ionisation</td></tr>
      <tr><td>HClO, HNO₂ (weak acids)</td><td>Partial ionisation only</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="kbox kbox-red" style="margin-top:14px;">
    <span class="kbox-label">Non-Electrolytes — Do NOT ionise</span>
    Sucrose (C₁₂H₂₂O₁₁), ethanol (C₂H₅OH), glucose (C₆H₁₂O₆), acetone, CO₂ (as a gas), SO₃, CCl₄, toluene, benzene<br><br>
    <strong>TRAP 1:</strong> Metal aluminium (Al) conducts electricity — but it is NOT an electrolyte. Metals conduct via delocalised electrons (metallic bonding), not by ionising in solution.<br>
    <strong>TRAP 2:</strong> CO₂ is a non-electrolyte. Even though CO₂ + H₂O ⇌ H₂CO₃, it is the H₂CO₃ that partially ionises, NOT CO₂ itself.<br>
    <strong>TRAP 3:</strong> Helium (He) is a noble gas — definitely not an electrolyte.
  </div>
</div>

<!-- COMMON MISTAKES 3.5 -->
<div class="mistake-section">
  <div class="ms-head">❌ Common Mistakes — Lesson 3.5</div>
  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "Aluminium (Al) is an electrolyte because it conducts electricity."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: Aluminium is a metal that conducts via delocalised electrons. Electrolytes are COMPOUNDS that ionise in water. Al is a free element, not a compound.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">Electrolyte = compound → ionises in water → ions conduct. Metal = free element → conducts via metallic bonding → NOT an electrolyte.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "NaCl and CH₃COOH are both electrolytes, so they both have pH = 7 in solution."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: NaCl forms a neutral solution (pH=7). CH₃COOH is a weak acid — it ionises partially → acidic solution (pH &lt; 7, about pH 3 for 0.1 mol/L).</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">Being an electrolyte doesn't tell you the pH. Strong acids → low pH. Strong bases → high pH. Neutral salts (like NaCl) → pH=7.</div>
  </div>
</div>

