<div class="summary-section" id="ch3-summary">
  <div class="sum-head">📌 Chapter 3 Summary — What You MUST Own</div>
  <div class="must-own-grid">
    <div class="must-item">
      <div class="mi-title">1. Electron Configuration</div>
      <div class="mi-body">K (Z=19) ends in 4s¹ (NOT 3d¹). P (Z=15) outer = 3s²3p³. F is Period 2, VIIA. Cl is Period 3, VIIA. Period = shells. Group = valence electrons. Fill 4s before 3d.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="must-item">
      <div class="mi-title">2. Periodic Trends</div>
      <div class="mi-body">Across period: radius decreases, ionisation energy increases, electronegativity increases. Down group: radius increases, metallic character increases. F has smallest atomic radius. K has largest among first 20.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="must-item">
      <div class="mi-title">3. Bond Types</div>
      <div class="mi-body">Na₂O₂ = ionic + covalent (O–O peroxide bond). NaOH = ionic + covalent (O–H). KCl = ionic only. CO₂ = covalent only. NH₄Cl = ionic + covalent. Test: does it have a polyatomic ion? If yes → usually ionic + covalent.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="must-item">
      <div class="mi-title">4. Reaction Rate Ratios</div>
      <div class="mi-body">v(A):v(B) = stoichiometric ratio. For N₂+3H₂→2NH₃: v(N₂):v(H₂):v(NH₃) = 1:3:2. Catalyst increases rate of BOTH directions equally — does NOT shift equilibrium. More volume = lower rate.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="must-item">
      <div class="mi-title">5. Equilibrium — The Only Rule</div>
      <div class="mi-body">At equilibrium: forward rate = reverse rate. Concentrations are CONSTANT (not necessarily equal). Adding inert gas at constant volume → no shift. Catalyst → no shift. Temperature change → only factor that changes Kc.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="must-item">
      <div class="mi-title">6. Le Chatelier's Principle</div>
      <div class="mi-body">↑T → endothermic direction. ↓T → exothermic direction. ↑P → fewer gas moles side. ↑[reactant] → forward. Remove product → forward. For 2HI⇌H₂+I₂: pressure has NO effect (equal gas moles both sides).</div>
    </div>
    <div class="must-item">
      <div class="mi-title">7. Valid Equilibrium Indicators</div>
      <div class="mi-body">✓ Same species, opposite directions: v(A formed) = v(A consumed). ✗ Same direction different species: v(A consumed) = ½v(B consumed) — just stoichiometry. ✓ Colour constant. ✓ Pressure constant (variable volume).</div>
    </div>
    <div class="must-item">
      <div class="mi-title">8. Electrolytes</div>
      <div class="mi-body">Strong: HCl, HNO₃, H₂SO₄, NaOH, KOH, Ca(OH)₂, soluble salts. Weak: CH₃COOH, NH₃·H₂O, H₂CO₃, HF, HClO. Non-electrolytes: sucrose, ethanol, CO₂, glucose. Al metal = NOT an electrolyte (free element).</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

