<div class="card">
  <h4>Common Laboratory Apparatus</h4>
  <table class="ctable">
    <tr><th>Apparatus</th><th>Purpose</th><th>Key feature</th></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Measuring cylinder</strong></td><td>Accurately measure liquid volume</td><td>Graduated markings; read at meniscus bottom</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Beaker</strong></td><td>Hold, mix, heat solutions</td><td>Approximate markings only (±5%); NOT for accurate volume</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Conical flask (Erlenmeyer)</strong></td><td>Reactions, titrations</td><td>Triangular shape; swirl without spilling</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Round-bottom flask</strong></td><td>Gas generation, distillation</td><td>Withstands heating; used in Kipp's generator</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Burette</strong></td><td>Precise volume delivery (titrations)</td><td>Calibrated to 0.1 mL; more precise than cylinder</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Balance</strong></td><td>Measure mass</td><td>Measures mass (g), NOT volume</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Separating funnel</strong></td><td>Liquid-liquid extraction</td><td>Stopcock controls flow; used in extraction</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Gas collection bottle</strong></td><td>Collect gases over water</td><td>Only for water-insoluble gases</td></tr>
  </table>
  <div class="etip"><p>The <strong>measuring cylinder</strong> is for accurately measuring liquid volume. A beaker has approximate markings only — do not use it for accurate volume measurement. The balance measures MASS, not volume.</p></div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h4>Properties of Concentrated H₂SO₄ — Must Know!</h4>
  <div class="g3">
    <div class="kbox kbox-blue">
      <span class="kbox-label">Hygroscopicity (吸水性)</span>
      Absorbs water vapour from surrounding gases.<br><br>
      This is why concentrated H₂SO₄ is used as a <strong>drying agent</strong> for gases.<br><br>
      The gas passes through concentrated H₂SO₄ and the water vapour is absorbed.
    </div>
    <div class="kbox kbox-amber">
      <span class="kbox-label">Dehydrating Property (脱水性)</span>
      Removes H and O from compounds in the ratio H:O = 2:1 (same as water).<br><br>
      Example: charring sugar<br>
      C₁₂H₂₂O₁₁ →(conc H₂SO₄) 12C + 11H₂O<br><br>
      This removes structural –OH and –H groups, not just free water.
    </div>
    <div class="kbox kbox-red">
      <span class="kbox-label">Oxidising Property (氧化性)</span>
      Concentrated H₂SO₄ oxidises metals, non-metals, and some compounds.<br><br>
      Cu + 2H₂SO₄(conc) →(Δ) CuSO₄ + SO₂↑ + 2H₂O<br>
      C + 2H₂SO₄(conc) →(Δ) CO₂↑ + 2SO₂↑ + 2H₂O<br><br>
      Dilute H₂SO₄ does NOT have this oxidising property.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="kbox kbox-teal" style="margin-top:12px;">
    <span class="kbox-label">EXAM TRAP: Which property makes H₂SO₄ a drying agent?</span>
    Answer: <strong>Hygroscopicity</strong> (absorbs water from gas stream). NOT the dehydrating property (which removes H₂O from compounds). These are different things! The CSCA exam has tested this distinction directly (Jan 2026 Q30).
  </div>
  <div class="kbox kbox-red" style="margin-top:10px;">
    <span class="kbox-label">Gases that CANNOT be dried with concentrated H₂SO₄</span>
    • NH₃ — reacts with H₂SO₄: 2NH₃ + H₂SO₄ → (NH₄)₂SO₄ (acid-base reaction)<br>
    • HBr, HI — oxidised by concentrated H₂SO₄: H₂SO₄ + 2HBr → SO₂ + Br₂ + 2H₂O<br>
    Use: anhydrous CaCl₂ (for most gases) or CaO/alkali (for NH₃)
  </div>
</div>

<!-- COMMON MISTAKES 4.1 -->
<div class="mistake-section">
  <div class="ms-head">❌ Common Mistakes — Lesson 4.1</div>
  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "Concentrated H₂SO₄ dries gases due to its dehydrating property."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: It dries gases due to <strong>hygroscopicity</strong> — it absorbs water vapour. The dehydrating property refers to removing structural water from compounds (like charring sugar). Different property!</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">Drying a gas = absorbing water vapour from the gas stream = hygroscopicity. Dehydrating = removing H₂O from organic molecules by breaking bonds.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "A beaker is used for accurately measuring liquid volume."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: A beaker has approximate markings (±5%) — it is for holding, mixing, and heating. The measuring cylinder is used for accurate volume measurement.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">On the CSCA exam: Q2 in Jan 2026 asks which instrument accurately measures liquid volume. Answer: measuring cylinder (NOT beaker, NOT balance).</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "NH₃ gas can be dried using concentrated H₂SO₄."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: NH₃ reacts with H₂SO₄: 2NH₃ + H₂SO₄ → (NH₄)₂SO₄. The drying agent would consume the gas! NH₃ must be dried with alkali (CaO or KOH solid).</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">Basic gases (NH₃) cannot be dried with acidic drying agents. Reducing gases (HBr, HI) cannot be dried with oxidising drying agents.</div>
  </div>
</div>

