    <tr><td><strong>Cl₂</strong></td><td>MnO₂ + conc. HCl, heat (Δ)</td><td>MnO₂ + 4HCl(conc) →(Δ) MnCl₂ + Cl₂↑ + 2H₂O</td><td>Bubble through saturated NaCl(aq) to remove HCl; dry with conc. H₂SO₄</td></tr>
  </table>

  <div class="etip"><p>
    <strong>Catalyst for O₂ from H₂O₂:</strong> MnO₂ (manganese dioxide). This is from Jan 2026 Q31 — the catalyst for H₂O₂ decomposition. Different from KClO₃ which also uses MnO₂ but requires heat.<br>
    <strong>Why use marble + dilute HCl for CO₂</strong> (not Na₂CO₃ + HCl)? Na₂CO₃ reacts too vigorously (exothermic, hard to control). Marble reacts slowly and controllably at room temperature.
  </p></div>
