<div class="lesson-start" id="l4-3">
  <span class="lesson-tag lt-u4">Lesson 4.3</span>
  <h3>Identification of Gases</h3>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h4>Gas Identification Tests — Complete Reference</h4>
  <table class="ctable">
    <tr><th>Gas</th><th>M (g/mol)</th><th>vs Air (M≈29)</th><th>Test</th><th>Observation</th></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>H₂</strong></td><td>2</td><td>Much lighter</td><td>Apply burning splint to tube mouth</td><td>Burns with pale blue flame; "pop" if mixed with air</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>O₂</strong></td><td>32</td><td>Slightly heavier</td><td>Insert glowing (not burning) splint into gas</td><td>Glowing splint <strong>reignites</strong> (bursts into flame)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>CO₂</strong></td><td>44</td><td>Heavier</td><td>Bubble through limewater Ca(OH)₂</td><td>Limewater turns <strong>milky white</strong> (CaCO₃↓); clears with excess CO₂</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>NH₃</strong></td><td>17</td><td>Lighter</td><td>Damp red litmus paper; or HCl rod</td><td>Red litmus turns <strong>blue</strong>; white smoke (NH₄Cl) with HCl</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Cl₂</strong></td><td>71</td><td>Much heavier</td><td>Moist litmus paper; or moist starch-iodide paper</td><td>Litmus turns red then <strong>decolourises</strong>; starch-iodide paper turns blue-black</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>SO₂</strong></td><td>64</td><td>Heavier</td><td>Acidified KMnO₄ solution; or limewater</td><td>KMnO₄ <strong>decolourises</strong> (purple→colourless); limewater turns milky (but clears faster than CO₂)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>CO</strong></td><td>28</td><td>Slightly lighter</td><td>Burn; or pass over heated CuO (black)</td><td>Burns with blue flame; CuO turns red (Cu) — CO reduces CuO</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>HCl</strong></td><td>36.5</td><td>Heavier</td><td>Moist blue litmus; or AgNO₃ solution</td><td>Litmus turns red; AgNO₃ → white AgCl↓ precipitate</td></tr>
  </table>
  <div class="etip"><p>
    <strong>O₂ test:</strong> Glowing splint that reignites = O₂. Do NOT use a burning splint (the gas could explode if it's H₂).<br>
    <strong>CO₂ vs SO₂:</strong> Both turn limewater milky. Distinguish by: SO₂ also decolourises acidified KMnO₄ (purple→colourless); CO₂ does NOT decolourise KMnO₄.<br>
    <strong>Cl₂ bleaching:</strong> Dry Cl₂ does NOT bleach. Cl₂ must first dissolve in water to form HClO, which then bleaches. Dry Cl₂ turns litmus red (acid) but doesn't decolourise it.
  </p></div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h4>Gas Collection Methods</h4>
  <table class="ctable">
    <tr><th>Method</th><th>Condition needed</th><th>Suitable gases</th><th>NOT suitable for</th></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Water displacement</strong></td><td>Insoluble in water</td><td>H₂, O₂, NO, N₂, CO, CH₄</td><td>NH₃, HCl, SO₂, Cl₂ (all soluble)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Upward air displacement</strong></td><td>Gas is lighter than air (M &lt; 29)</td><td>H₂ (M=2), NH₃ (M=17), CH₄ (M=16)</td><td>CO₂, Cl₂, SO₂ (all denser)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Downward air displacement</strong></td><td>Gas is denser than air (M &gt; 29)</td><td>CO₂ (M=44), Cl₂ (M=71), SO₂ (M=64), HCl (M=36.5)</td><td>H₂, NH₃, CH₄ (all lighter)</td></tr>
  </table>
  <div class="kbox kbox-teal" style="margin-top:12px;">
    <span class="kbox-label">Which gases can use BOTH water displacement AND air displacement?</span>
    <strong>H₂:</strong> water displacement ✓ (insoluble) + upward air displacement ✓ (M=2 &lt; 29) → TWO methods<br>
    <strong>O₂:</strong> water displacement ✓ (insoluble) + downward air displacement ✓ (M=32 &gt; 29) → TWO methods<br>
    <strong>NH₃:</strong> only upward air displacement (too soluble for water displacement)<br>
    <strong>CO₂:</strong> only downward air displacement (dissolves in water too much for water displacement)
  </div>
</div>

<!-- COMMON MISTAKES 4.3 -->
<div class="mistake-section">
  <div class="ms-head">❌ Common Mistakes — Lesson 4.3</div>
  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "CO₂ can be collected by water displacement."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: CO₂ is moderately soluble in water → cannot be collected by water displacement. Use downward air displacement (M=44 &gt; 29).</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">Water displacement only works for gases that are insoluble in water (H₂, O₂, NO, N₂). CO₂ dissolves significantly in water.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "Pass SO₂ through limewater to distinguish it from CO₂."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: BOTH SO₂ and CO₂ turn limewater milky. To distinguish them, use acidified KMnO₄: SO₂ decolourises it (purple→colourless), but CO₂ does NOT.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">SO₂ is a reducing agent; it reduces KMnO₄. CO₂ is not a reducing agent. This is the definitive test to tell them apart.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "Inserting a glowing splint into a gas — it reignites — this proves the gas is O₂."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: A glowing splint reigniting IS the test for O₂. But remember: a BURNING splint extinguishing = CO₂ or N₂. A burning splint burning brighter = O₂ (but glowing splint test is definitive).</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">Use glowing splint (not burning) for the O₂ test. The glowing splint reignites in O₂ because O₂ supports combustion and provides the oxidiser needed to relight it.</div>
  </div>
</div>

