<div class="card">
  <h4>Haber Process — Ammonia Synthesis</h4>
  <div class="eq">
<span class="ec">Haber Process</span>
N₂(g) + 3H₂(g) ⇌ 2NH₃(g)    ΔH = −92 kJ/mol (exothermic)
<span class="ec">Conditions: ~450–500°C, 150–300 atm, Fe catalyst (with promoters Al₂O₃, K₂O)</span>
  </div>

  <table class="ctable" style="margin-top:14px;">
    <tr><th>Condition</th><th>Le Chatelier Analysis</th><th>Why this choice?</th></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>High pressure (150–300 atm)</strong></td><td>4 gas moles → 2 gas moles. ↑P → side with fewer gas moles (right) → more NH₃</td><td>Thermodynamically favoured; but equipment cost ↑ with pressure</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Moderate temperature (450–500°C)</strong></td><td>Exothermic forward: lower T → more NH₃. But lower T = very slow rate.</td><td>COMPROMISE: high enough for acceptable rate, low enough for acceptable yield</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Fe catalyst</strong></td><td>No shift in equilibrium, but reaches equilibrium much faster</td><td>Allows acceptable rate at moderate temperature without shifting position</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Remove NH₃ as it forms</strong></td><td>Removing product → shifts equilibrium right → more NH₃</td><td>Continuously drives the reaction forward by removing product</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Recycle N₂ and H₂</strong></td><td>Adds back unreacted starting materials</td><td>Efficiency — unreacted N₂ and H₂ are not wasted</td></tr>
  </table>

  <div class="kbox kbox-amber" style="margin-top:14px;">
    <span class="kbox-label">Contact Process — Sulfuric Acid Manufacturing (also tested)</span>
    <strong>Step 1:</strong> Burn sulfur: S + O₂ → SO₂<br>
    <strong>Step 2:</strong> Oxidise SO₂: 2SO₂ + O₂ ⇌ 2SO₃ (V₂O₅ catalyst, ~450°C) — exothermic<br>
    <strong>Step 3:</strong> Absorb in concentrated H₂SO₄: SO₃ + H₂SO₄ → H₂S₂O₇ (oleum)<br>
    <strong>Step 4:</strong> Dilute oleum: H₂S₂O₇ + H₂O → 2H₂SO₄<br><br>
    Why not dissolve SO₃ directly in water? Produces acid mist (very fine H₂SO₄ droplets) that are hard to collect. Concentrated H₂SO₄ absorbs SO₃ efficiently.
  </div>
</div>

