    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "Using very high temperature in the Haber process increases NH₃ yield."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: The reaction is exothermic, so LOWER temperature → higher yield (more NH₃ at equilibrium). But too low T = too slow. The 450°C is a compromise between rate and yield.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">Rate and yield are in opposition for exothermic reactions: higher T = faster but lower yield. The Haber process uses a moderate temperature as a compromise.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div class="mi-wrong">✗ WRONG: "The Fe catalyst in the Haber process increases the NH₃ yield."</div>
    <div class="mi-right">✓ RIGHT: The catalyst does NOT change the equilibrium position or yield. It only speeds up the reaction to reach equilibrium faster. The yield (amount of NH₃ at equilibrium) depends on T and P, not the catalyst.</div>
    <div class="mi-explain">Catalyst = no shift in equilibrium = no change in final yield. It allows you to reach the same equilibrium state faster.</div>
  </div>
</div>

