<div class="summary-section" id="ch4-summary">
  <div class="sum-head">📌 Chapter 4 Summary — What You MUST Own</div>
  <div class="must-own-grid">
    <div class="must-item">
      <div class="mi-title">1. Lab Apparatus</div>
      <div class="mi-body">Measuring cylinder = accurate volume. Beaker = approximate (~±5%). Balance = mass (not volume). Gas collection bottle = water-insoluble gases only. Separating funnel = extraction (immiscible liquids).</div>
    </div>
    <div class="must-item">
      <div class="mi-title">2. Concentrated H₂SO₄ Properties</div>
      <div class="mi-body">Drying gases = hygroscopicity (absorbs water vapour). Charring sugar = dehydrating property. Reacting with Cu = oxidising property. CANNOT dry: NH₃ (acid-base), HBr, HI (redox).</div>
    </div>
    <div class="must-item">
      <div class="mi-title">3. Gas Preparation Catalysts</div>
      <div class="mi-body">O₂ from KClO₃ = MnO₂ catalyst + heat. O₂ from H₂O₂ = MnO₂ catalyst (no heat). CO₂ from CaCO₃ = dilute HCl (NOT H₂SO₄ — CaSO₄ coats marble). NH₃ from NH₄Cl = Ca(OH)₂ + heat.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="must-item">
      <div class="mi-title">4. Gas Identification</div>
      <div class="mi-body">O₂: glowing splint reignites. CO₂: limewater milky. NH₃: red litmus turns blue. H₂: pale blue flame + pop. Cl₂: litmus red then decolourises. SO₂: KMnO₄ decolourises (CO₂ does NOT). CO: reduces CuO (black→red).</div>
    </div>
    <div class="must-item">
      <div class="mi-title">5. Collection Methods</div>
      <div class="mi-body">H₂: water displacement + upward air (M=2). O₂: water displacement + downward air (M=32). CO₂: downward only (dissolves in water). NH₃: upward only (too soluble). N₂, CO: water displacement only (M≈air).</div>
    </div>
    <div class="must-item">
      <div class="mi-title">6. Separation Methods</div>
      <div class="mi-body">Filtration: solid from liquid. Distillation: different boiling points. Extraction: immiscible solvents (separating funnel). Sublimation: purify I₂. Recrystallisation: purify solids. NaHCO₃ from Na₂CO₃: heat (decomposition).</div>
    </div>
    <div class="must-item">
      <div class="mi-title">7. Haber Process</div>
      <div class="mi-body">N₂ + 3H₂ ⇌ 2NH₃ (exothermic). High P → more NH₃ (fewer gas moles). Moderate T (450°C) = compromise rate vs yield. Fe catalyst → faster equilibrium, no yield change. Remove NH₃ as formed → shifts right.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="must-item">
      <div class="mi-title">8. Bleaching & Dry Cl₂</div>
      <div class="mi-body">Dry Cl₂ does NOT bleach. Must dissolve in water to form HClO first. HClO bleaches by oxidation. KClO₃ ≠ bleach. NaCl ≠ bleach. HClO decomposes in light: 2HClO → 2HCl + O₂. This is why Cl₂ water stored in dark.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

